[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Oversight and accountability [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]3.8[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Free schools are subject to greater examination than almost any other type of state
[normal]-funded
[normal] school. Not only are they subject to the same accountability framework
[normal] 
[normal]as 
[normal]any Academy
[normal] but they face additional levels of scrutiny. The political controversy which has surround
[normal]ed
[normal] the policy means that Free Schools are the subject of intense analysis from local and national media as well as other interest groups. Even 
[normal]more important
[normal], because
[normal] parents have actively chosen a Free School, often before it even physically exists, they have high expectations of what the school will deliver and are more engaged in holding it to account.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.9[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Once open, Free Schools have the same legal status as Academies
[normal] which is formally set out in a Funding Agreement
[normal], signed by the Secretary of State and the 
[normal]Company Limited by Guarantee that operates the new academy
[normal]. Free Schools are expected to adopt a model funding agreement which, amongst other 
[normal]things, states that t
[normal]hey must follow the School Admissions Code, be inspected by Ofsted, publish their results and provide a broad and balanced curriculum, which cannot teach anything counter to fundamental British values, or creationism.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.10[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There is a seven year notice period i
[normal]n standard Free School funding agreements
[normal]. 
[normal]I
[normal]f a Free School is found to be in breach of it any time before then, the Secretary of State 
[normal]has the power to 
[normal]terminate 
[normal]the agreement. 
[normal]This power has proved reasonably
[normal] effective – it was the threat of terminating 
[normal]the funding agreement that allowed the 
[normal]DfE 
[normal]to 
[normal]take action 
[normal]in terms of the governance of
[normal] 
[normal]Al-Madinah
[normal] in Derby
[normal] 
[normal]– requiring them 
[normal]to 
[normal]accept new 
[normal]management
[normal] or face termination
[normal].
[normal] It is worth noting however that there is no defined point at which an agreement is re
[normal]viewed and, apart from this power to terminate, there is no power to intervene or pass management of 
[normal]a Free School or an 
[normal]academy to someone else. The need for these wider powers and the standard period of funding agreements should be 
[normal]reviewed to ensure 
[normal]that they allow swift and decisive action can be taken in cases where there are serious concerns about the school
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.11[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The EFA oversees the financial management and governance of Free Schools through a named contact for each school
[normal] 
[normal]and 
[normal]who visits the
[normal]m in thei
[normal]r
[normal] first term
[normal]. DfE Education Advisers 
[normal]also visit new schools 
[normal]in the autumn term of each of the first two years of 
[normal]operation
[normal]. 
[normal]Finally, 
[normal]Ofsted inspects the school within two years of opening 
[normal]assessing against the same standards 
[normal]required of all state schools. 
[normal] These assessments are used to identify potential risks to schools and risk rate each school, with particular concerns being escalated through further monitoring. 
[normal]It was through this route that the issues at Discovery New School
[normal] in Crawley
[normal] were identified 
[normal]and 
[normal]subsequently 
[normal]addressed.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.12[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Secretary of State can take a number of actions in relation to failing Free Schools:
[normal]—
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Allow Ofsted to follow its standard processes for all state schools through subsequent inspection and monitoring; 
[normal]—
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]D
[normal]emand a compreh
[normal]ensive 
[normal]plan to address failure; 
[normal]—
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Intervene to appoint and rem
[normal]ove governors; 
[normal]—
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Transfer the running of the school to a different Academy sponsor; or
[normal]—
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Terminate the school’s funding agreement and close the school
[normal]3.13[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Attention has been drawn to the weaknesses of a small number of the first Free Schools, which have been exposed either by inspection from Ofsted, investigation by the EFA or by individuals bringing matters to the attention of the DfE. In all cases the resp
[normal]onse has been both swift and practical. There is little evidence to suggest that intervention would have been any swifter if these schools had been s
[normal]ubject to LA oversight – for instance 
[normal]there are currently more than 350 maintained schools in special measu
[normal]res, nearly a third of which have had that status for more than a year.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]If Free Schools are to reach their full potential in 
[normal]improving
[normal] standards
[normal], 
[normal]using their academy freedoms
[normal], 
[normal]introducing innovation into
[normal] the system
[normal], 
[normal]allowing outstanding providers to open new schools, encouraging competition
[normal] and increasing
[normal] the number of good school places in the system
[normal], it is important
[normal] 
[normal]that both the approval and oversight systems to which Free Schools are subject are designed to protec
[normal]t and encourage their distinctive features and the unique addition they make to the schools system
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Underlying these distinctive features is the fact that new 
[normal]providers and 
[normal]innovations have 
[normal]the potential to raise educational standards 
[normal]by 
[normal]bring
[normal]ing
[normal] challenge
[normal] and competition to existing systems, even if this means creating a surplus of places. 
[normal]Any 
[normal]revisions to the 
[normal]approval 
[normal]and 
[normal]oversight systems
[normal], especially if they are designed 
[normal]to accommodate all a
[normal]cademies or schools more widely, will 
[normal]therefore 
[normal]need to be caref
[normal]ully assessed to ensure they do 
[normal]not create unforeseen 
[normal]barriers
[normal] or stifle the development and potential of the Free School programme in particular
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]This need is particularly a
[normal]cute when it comes to
[normal] the
[normal] 
[normal]approvals[bold] 
[normal]process where it is important to
[normal] ensure that good schools continue to be approved to open where they are needed
[normal] and wanted by local parents
[normal] – including
[normal] when they will be competing with existing 
[normal]underperforming 
[normal]provision
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Local authorities and local schools, as providers with 
[normal]responsibil
[normal]ity for managing and overseeing 
[normal]existing 
[normal]schools
[normal] in a given region
[normal] 
[normal]may be inclined to resist 
[normal]when it
[normal] comes to considering the introduction of alternative school
[normal]s
[normal] that might challenge the status quo. In light of this, 
[normal]NSN believes 
[normal]t
[normal]he approval process for Free Schools should remain independent of Local Authorities and other local existing providers. 
[normal]While it is undeniable the 
[normal]Free School programme has a strong momentum behind it
[normal], the scale of growth
[normal], even in the medium term,
[normal] is likel
[normal]y to be small enough that it should be possible to manage centrally.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.5[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Similarly, there are unique challenges in setting up an entirely new school and the right support and challenge is needed to ensure schools are set up to succeed not fail. 
[normal]Strong accou
[normal]ntability and performance 
[normal]criteria
[normal] are vital to the success of the Free School programme. In NSN’s view, the current framework is robust and, alongside the Ofsted systems that apply to all schools, has allowed the DfE/EFA
[normal]/Ofsted
[normal] to take swift and decisive 
[normal]action where necessary.  However, given the rate of growth in the number of Free Schools and academies more widely, the DfE’s capacity to monitor risks centrally and interv
[normal]ene where appropriate is becoming
[normal] 
[normal]stretched so it is 
[normal]a sensible next step to fully 
[normal]review
[normal] whether 
[normal]the current framework will remain fit for purpose
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]December 2013
[normal]APPENDIX[bold]: [bold]The [bold]current approval process[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]As it stands, the approval process falls broadly into two phases:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The application phase [bold]Groups wanting to set up a Free School rightly have to 
[normal]complete a demanding application process. Aside from the first year of the programme – when 
[normal]groups completed a much briefer initial application and then received paid for support to turn this into a detailed 
[normal]business 
[normal]plan
[normal] – all Free School applicants have 
[normal]had to undertake significant work 
[normal]without any financial support (except those receiv
[normal]ing small grants from NSN). Currently, this includes:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]To gather evidence of demand
[normal], M
[normal]ainstream Free School
[normal] applicant
[normal]s 
[normal]must
[normal] show 
[normal]that 
[normal]local parents
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]with
[normal] children of 
[normal]relevant
[normal] age
[normal]s
[normal] to attend the 
[normal]s
[normal]chool when it opens
[normal], would choose it as a first choice, were it to open
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Special and AP Free School applicants must show that they have both the
[normal] support of relevant parents/young people and in principle financial commitments from relevant commissioners to purchase places at the school
[normal], over and
[normal] above the central funding (£10,000 and £8
[normal],
[normal]000
[normal] respectively) available to them
[normal]. 
[normal]I
[normal]deally
[normal], applicants have to show that the school would be 
[normal]several times oversubscribed
[normal] in its first two years of operation
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Once submitt
[normal]ed, these applications are 
[normal]assessed by dedicated teams at the DfE/EFA and, where they have been submitted by an existing Acade
[normal]my sponsor, discussed with the Academies division to analyse the sponsor’s capacity to expand further.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Following this, a number of applicants are invited for interview by a panel which includes representatives from the DfE, EFA, external educational advis
[normal]ers and independent experts. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The rigour of the application phase can be seen in’ the relatively low success rate of applicants, with only 26% of the 1103 applications received by the DfE being progressed to the pre-opening phase
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The pre-opening phas[bold]e[bold]If successful 
[normal]at interview
[normal], groups are
[normal] then
[normal] 
[normal]provisionally 
[normal]‘approved’ to open a 
[normal]Free S
[normal]chool
[normal]. Groups receive funding from the DfE
[normal] (currently £220,000 for primary schools and £300,000 for secondary/all-through schools) in order to ensure the school ready to open – including recruiting staff, developing education plans and policies, building financial systems and recruiting pupils. Th
[normal]ey must also conduct a statutory consultation with the local community to ask whether stakeholders believe the school should open, and respond to any concerns.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Groups also receive substantial support at this stage with finding, securing and developing a s
[normal]ite with the EFA taking all key decisions. Aside from this, the role of the DfE is largely to provide oversight and challenge to the project – through a dedicated project lead, education and finance advisers, who hold regular checkpoint meetings to review 
[normal]its progress. 
[normal]If 
[normal]this is found to be unsatisfactory at any stage then the 
[normal]project may be cancelled, or the opening 
[normal]of the school delayed. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Before being allowed to open, the school must also 
[normal]pass
[normal] two further requirements. First, it is inspected by
[normal] Ofsted t
[normal]o ensure 
[normal]that it meets 
[normal]necessary standards
[normal] around the quality of its premises and the provision of policies relating to issues such as the welfare, health and safety of pupils
[normal]. Secondly, DfE officials must 
[normal]conduct an
[normal] assessment of the
[normal] Free School
[normal]’s impact
[normal] on other schools in the area. Only at this stage, if all other requirements have been fulfilled, will the Secretary of State sign a funding agreement with the school which allows it to formally open. 
[normal]&#xa0;
